IV. TO CALLIOPE

Descende eoelo et die age tibia

ESCEND from heaven and a long lay inspire, My queen, Calliope — whether thy choice Be for the pipe with a clear ringing voice, Or thou prefer the chords of Phoebus' lyre.

Hear you ? or does a charming phantasy Delude me? for I seem to hear — and stray Through sacred groves where genia] breezes play, And running waters murmur pleasantly.

When lost on Vultur, the Apulian Steep, Wandering beyond my own Apulia, The doves brought leaves to screen me where Ι lay —

Thus ran the legend -- wearied and asleep. 122
